¬ß Why ‚¶â
¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ We want a notion for a correspondence between two sets. ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬ß Definition ‚¶â
¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ A ‚ù¨function‚ù≠ $f$ (or ‚ù¨correspondence‚ù≠, ‚ù¨mapping‚ù≠, ‚ù¨map‚ù≠)
    ‚ù¨from‚ù≠ a set $X$ ‚ù¨to‚ù≠ a set $Y$ is a‚ê£
    <a href='/sheets/relations.html'>
      ‚Äñ relation ‚¶â
    </a>
    ‚ê£whose domain is $X$ and whose range is a subset of $Y$,
    such that for each $x ‚àà X$,
    ùç´ ‚¶ä
      ‚Ä£ there exists $y ‚àà Y$ so that $(x, y) ‚àà f$ ‚¶â

      ‚Ä£ if $(x,y) ‚àà f$ and $(x,z) ‚àà f$, then $y = z$; where
        $y$ and $z$ are in $Y$ ‚¶â
    ‚¶â‚¶â

  ‚Äñ We often summarize these two conditions by saying: to every
    element $x ‚àà X$ there corresponds a ‚ù¨unique‚ù≠ element $y ‚àà
    Y$ so that $(x, y) ‚àà f$. ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ We call this unique element $y ‚àà Y$ the ‚ù¨result‚ù≠ of the
    function ‚ù¨at‚ù≠ the ‚ù¨argument‚ù≠ $x$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ We call $Y$ ‚Äπa‚Ä∫ ‚ù¨codomain‚ù≠‚Äînotice our use of the word ‚Äúa‚Äù,
    since the codomain is not a property of the function. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ If the range is $Y$ we say that $f$ is a function from
    $X$ ‚ù¨onto‚ù≠ $Y$ (or call $f$ ‚ù¨onto‚ù≠, ‚ù¨surjective‚ù≠). ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ If distinct elements of $X$ are mapped to distinct elements
    of $Y$, we say that the function is ‚ù¨one-to-one‚ù≠ (or
    ‚ù¨injective‚ù≠). ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬∂ ‚¶ä
  <!-- We know functions by how the associate elements of their codomain with elements of their domain.  -->

  ‚Äñ We say that the function ‚ù¨maps‚ù≠ (or ‚ù¨takes‚ù≠) elements from
    the domain to the codomain. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ Since the word ‚Äúfunction‚Äù and the verb ‚Äúmaps‚Äù connote
    activity, some authors refer to the set of ordered pairs as
    the ‚ù¨graph‚ù≠ of a function and avoid defining the term
    ‚Äúfunction‚Äù as we have, in terms of sets. ‚¶â

‚¶â

¬ß¬ß Notation ‚¶â
¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ Given sets $X$ and $Y$, we abbreviate the statement that
    the object denoted by $f$ is a function whose domain is a
    $X$ and whose codomain is a set $Y$ by
    ‚óá ‚¶ä
      ‚Äñ f: X ‚Üí Y ‚¶â
    ‚¶â‚¶â

  ‚Äñ We read the notation aloud as ‚Äú$f$ from $X$ to $Y$.‚Äù ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ We emphasize again that the ‚Äπrange‚Ä∫ of $f$ need not be
    $Y$, but must necessarily be a subset. ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ We denote by $Y^X$ the set of functions from $X$ to $Y$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ This set is contained in the power set $\powerset{(X √ó Y)}$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ A reasonable but nonstandard notation is $X ‚Üí Y$, read as
    ‚Äú$A$ to $B$.‚Äù ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ All the following three statements have the same meaning:
    ‚óá ‚¶ä
      ‚Äñ f: X ‚Üí Y, \quad f ‚àà Y^X, \quad f ‚àà (X ‚Üí Y). ‚¶â
    ‚¶â‚¶â
‚¶â

¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ We tend to denote functions by lower case latin letters;
    especially $f$, $g$, and $h$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ $f$ is a mnemonic for function and $g$ and $h$ are nearby
    in the usual ordering of the‚ê£
    <a href='/sheets/letters.html#Latin_letters'>
      ‚Äñ Latin letters ‚¶â
    </a>
    . ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ Suppose $f: A ‚Üí B$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ For each element $a ‚àà A$, we denote the result of applying
    $f$ to $a$ by $f(a)$, read aloud ‚Äúf of a.‚Äù ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ We sometimes drop the parentheses, and write the result as
    $f_a$, read aloud as ‚Äúf sub a.‚Äù ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ Let $g: A √ó B ‚Üí C$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ We often write $g(a,b)$ or $g_{ab}$ instead of $g((a,b))$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ We read $g(a, b)$ aloud as ‚Äúg of a and b‚Äù. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ We read $g_{ab}$ aloud as ‚Äúg sub a b.‚Äù ‚¶â

