‚¶â

¬ß¬ß Examples ‚¶â
¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ If $X ‚äÇ Y$, the function $\Set{(x, y) ‚àà X √ó Y}{x = y}$
    is the ‚ù¨inclusion function‚ù≠ of $X$ into $Y$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ We often introduce such a function as ‚Äúthe function from
    $X$ to $Y$ defined by $f(x) = y$‚Äù. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ We mean by this that $f$ is a function and that we are
    specifying the appropraite ordered pairs using the statement,
    called ‚ù¨argument-value notation‚ù≠. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ The inclusion function of $X$ into $X$ is called the
    ‚ù¨identity function‚ù≠ of $X$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ If we view the identity function as a relation on $X$, it
    is the relation of equality on $X$. ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ The functions $f: (X √ó Y) ‚Üí X$ defined by $f(x, y) = x$
    is the ‚ù¨pair projection‚ù≠ of $X √ó Y$ ono $X$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ Similarly $g: (X √ó Y) ‚Üí Y$ defined by $g(x, y) = y$ is
    the pair projection of $X √ó Y$ onto $Y$. ‚¶â

  <!-- The range of $f$ is the first coordinate projection of $f$ and the range of $g$ is the second coordinate projection of $f$ (see \sheetref{ordered_pair_projections}{Ordered Pair Projections}). -->

  ‚Äñ The identity function is one-to-one and onto, the inclusion
    functions are one-to-one but not always onto, and the pair
    projections are usually not one-to-one. ‚¶â
‚¶â

